    <dsc type="combined">
      <c01 level="series">
        <did>
          <unittitle>Personal</unittitle>
        </did>
        <scopecontent>
          <p>The Personal series spans the dates 1893-1952. It includes a short unpublished biography of Pepper by collection donor Winston Wessels, written in 1963, which details his legal and military careers, as well as two autobiographical letters by Pepper, written in 1920 and 1952. The bulk of this series is made up of correspondence with family and friends in the United States and Canada. The letters provide a glimpse into relations between members of Pepper's extended family and details of daily life in pre-World War I Canada. These include discussions of current events and politics, particularly between 1900 and 1920. Letters from A.M. Dallas and Miles Pepper provide first-hand accounts of life in western Canada during the "boom" early in the century. The Pepper family genealogy by M.G. Reddon may be of use in determining family relationships.</p>
          <p>Samuel Pepper and his wife Katherine wrote to each other almost daily while he was serving in France (1918-1919) and this correspondence tells a great deal about the war as each of them experienced it. Other letters which describe war experiences are Robert Pepper's letters home from the Pacific in World War II; Samuel Pepper's correspondence with "war buddy" John LeFevre; and letters from a French acquaintance, Margaret Philbert. The latter contain vivid descriptions of life in France immediately following the Second World War. The A-Z folder contains letters to Pepper from Attorney General Grant Fellows and Alex Groesbeck written to Pepper while he was at the front in World War I.</p>
        </scopecontent>
